    "subtype": "equipment",
    "text": "Luck and good fortune bless the wielder of this *+3 greater striking shortsword*. *Luck blades* are crafted in a variety of styles, but their hilts or blades always incorporate symbols of luck, such as clovers, horseshoes, fish, ladybugs, or other symbols.",
    "traits": [
      {
        "alternate_link": {
          "alternate_type": "legacy",
          "aonid": 137,
          "game-obj": "Traits",
          "type": "alternate_link"
        },
        "classes": [
          "rare"
        ],
        "edition": "remastered",
        "game-id": "e4b0e4f5f4b3d4cad3bea67ec077e297",
        "game-obj": "Traits",
        "links": [
          {
            "alt": "Recall Knowledge",
            "aonid": 26,
            "game-obj": "Actions",
            "name": "Recall Knowledge",
            "type": "link"
          }
        ],
        "name": "Rare",
        "sources": [
          {
            "errata": {
              "alt": "2.0",
              "aonid": 216,
              "game-obj": "Sources",
              "name": "2.0",
              "type": "link"
            },
            "link": {
              "alt": "Player Core pg. 11",
              "aonid": 216,
              "game-obj": "Sources",
              "name": "Player Core pg. 11",
              "type": "link"
            },
            "name": "Player Core",
            "page": 11,
            "type": "source"
          }
        ],
        "text": "This rarity indicates that a rules element is very difficult to find in the game world. A rare feat, spell, item or the like is available to players only if the GM decides to include it in the game, typically through discovery during play. Creatures with this trait are rare. They typically can't be summoned. The DC of Recall Knowledge checks related to these creatures is increased by 5.",
        "type": "trait"
      },
      {
        "classes": [
          "trait"
        ],
        "edition": "legacy",
        "game-id": "dc277f983a39bb74b92ffada679a9c8a",
        "game-obj": "Traits",
        "name": "Divination",
        "sources": [
          {
            "errata": {
              "alt": "4.0",
              "aonid": 1,
              "game-obj": "Sources",
              "name": "4.0",
              "type": "link"
            },
            "link": {
              "alt": "Core Rulebook pg. 631",
              "aonid": 1,
              "game-obj": "Sources",
              "name": "Core Rulebook pg. 631",
              "type": "link"
            },
            "name": "Core Rulebook",
            "page": 631,
            "type": "source"
          }
        ],
        "text": "The divination school of magic typically involves obtaining or transferring information, or predicting events.",
        "type": "trait"
      },
      {
        "alternate_link": {
          "alternate_type": "legacy",
          "aonid": 76,
          "game-obj": "Traits",
          "type": "alternate_link"
        },
        "classes": [
          "trait"
        ],
        "edition": "remastered",
        "game-id": "7adeee5fc9bf211a4db10de37045506c",
        "game-obj": "Traits",
        "links": [
          {
            "alt": "misfortune",
            "aonid": 110,
            "game-obj": "Traits",
            "name": "misfortune",
            "type": "link"
          }
        ],
        "name": "Fortune",
        "sources": [
          {
            "errata": {
              "alt": "2.0",
              "aonid": 216,
              "game-obj": "Sources",
              "name": "2.0",
              "type": "link"
            },
            "link": {
              "alt": "Player Core pg. 401",
              "aonid": 216,
              "game-obj": "Sources",
              "name": "Player Core pg. 401",
              "type": "link"
            },
            "name": "Player Core",
            "page": 401,
            "type": "source"
          }
        ],
        "text": "A fortune effect beneficially alters how you roll your dice. You can never have more than one fortune effect alter a single roll. If multiple fortune effects would apply, you have to pick which to use. If a fortune effect and a misfortune effect would apply to the same roll, the two cancel each other out, and you roll normally.",
        "type": "trait"
      },
      {
        "alternate_link": {
          "alternate_type": "legacy",
          "aonid": 103,
          "game-obj": "Traits",
          "type": "alternate_link"
        },
        "classes": [
          "trait"
        ],
        "edition": "remastered",
        "game-id": "15e2d048ce93e7b648064b09972535bc",
        "game-obj": "Traits",
        "name": "Magical",
        "sources": [
          {
            "errata": {
              "alt": "2.0",
              "aonid": 216,
              "game-obj": "Sources",
              "name": "2.0",
              "type": "link"
            },
            "link": {
              "alt": "Player Core pg. 458",
              "aonid": 216,
              "game-obj": "Sources",
              "name": "Player Core pg. 458",
              "type": "link"
            },
            "name": "Player Core",
            "page": 458,
            "type": "source"
          }
        ],
        "text": "Something with the magical trait is imbued with magical energies not tied to a specific tradition of magic. Some items or effects are closely tied to a particular tradition of magic. In these cases, the item has the arcane, divine, occult, or primal trait instead of the magical trait. Any of these traits indicate that the item is magical.",
        "type": "trait"
      }
    ],
